# Progressive Refactor

## The 300-Line Rule

**When you are already modifying a file that exceeds 300 lines, extract the pieces you touch into separate files.**

This rule is NOT a reason to refactor files you are NOT touching. Do not add extra scope to a PR just to clean up unrelated files.

The trigger is simple:
- You open a file to make a change
- The file is >300 lines
- As part of your change, extract the logic you're adding/modifying into a properly-named layer file

## Layer Separation Pattern

Every domain area should follow this file separation. When a file grows past 300 lines, split it along these boundaries:

| File suffix | What goes there |
|-------------|-----------------|
| `*.types.ts` | TypeScript interfaces and type aliases only — no logic |
| `*.validators.ts` | Zod schemas for forms and API input validation |
| `*.service.ts` | Business logic — fetching, transforming, saving data |
| `*.domain.ts` | Domain constants, enums, helper functions specific to that domain |
| `*.hooks.ts` or `use*.ts` | React hooks that encapsulate state and data fetching |

Example — a `properties` domain that has grown:

```
lib/
  supply-properties-supabase.ts    → original (stays, or becomes service)
  supply-properties.types.ts       → Property, PropertyInsert, etc.
  supply-properties.validators.ts  → PropertyFormSchema, StatusSchema
  supply-properties.service.ts     → fetchProperty(), updateStatus()
  supply-properties.domain.ts      → STATUS_LABELS, ROLE_PERMISSIONS
```

## What to Extract vs What to Leave

**Extract:**
- A function you are modifying that has >50 lines of its own
- A set of types that are imported by >2 other files
- A Zod schema that is used in multiple places
- Business logic mixed into a React component

**Do NOT extract:**
- Logic you are not touching in this PR
- Small helpers (<10 lines) that are only used once
- Types that are only used in the file they're defined

## No Big Bang Refactors

Never refactor an entire domain in one PR just because one file was large. That creates huge diffs that are impossible to review and high risk for regressions.

The pattern: **leave the old file in place, extract the new piece into a properly-named file, import it from the old location.** The consumer code doesn't need to change.

```typescript
// supply-properties-supabase.ts — BEFORE (300+ lines, getting unwieldy)
export function fetchProperty(...) { ... }
export const PropertyFormSchema = z.object(...)  // 40 lines of Zod

// AFTER — extract only the validator, leave everything else
// supply-properties-supabase.ts
export { PropertyFormSchema } from './supply-properties.validators'  // re-export
export function fetchProperty(...) { ... }  // stays here

// supply-properties.validators.ts (new file, only created because you were editing it)
export const PropertyFormSchema = z.object(...)
```
